# Forge holds no model provider key of its own for chat — users bring their own
# credentials through the in-app Providers panel, and each is stored in an
# httpOnly cookie, never in the environment:
#   - a Hugging Face token for cloud chat
#   - an OpenAI-compatible connection for chat against your own provider
#   - an OpenAI-compatible connection for codegen (the AI that writes playgrounds)
#
# The ONE optional server-side key is the free codegen "taste" below. It's off by
# default: a cloned Forge without it is strictly bring-your-own.

# Optional. A Groq API key used to write a first-time visitor's first few
# playgrounds for free — the "taste" of the product before they bring their own
# codegen key. On a DEPLOY each browser gets a small fixed number of free
# generations (FREE_CODEGEN_LIMIT in lib/playground/codegen-provider.ts, tracked
# by an httpOnly cookie); everything after — regenerate, modify, new playgrounds
# — needs their own key. Running locally is never metered: it's your own key on
# your own machine. Get one at https://console.groq.com/keys
#
# You don't need this file at all to develop: bring a codegen key through the
# in-app Providers panel instead, which takes precedence over anything here.
GROQ_API_KEY=

# Set to 1 to actually turn the free tier on. GROQ_API_KEY alone does nothing.
#
# IMPORTANT: /api/codegen has no authentication. The per-browser counter cookie
# stops honest re-use, but a determined abuser can clear cookies to pull more
# free generations. Your real cost ceiling is a SPENDING CAP set on the Groq
# account itself — set one before enabling this on a public deploy, and size it
# knowing the per-visitor allowance multiplies your worst case. Left unset, every
# user brings their own codegen provider.
FORGE_FREE_CODEGEN=
